column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While inspecting a shipment of freight on the dock, a leak was noticed.  Approximately 1 liter of Potassium hydroxide solution released and impacted the freight and concrete.  The cause of release is unknown.  The free product was immediately contained to the concrete and cleaned up at the ORD facility.  BAX Global personnel performed the cleanup using a broom, shovel, gloves and absorbents.  BAX Global, Inc. generated approximately 1 pound of waste that will be over-packed in a recovery drum to await shipper notification for disposal.  There were no injuries or exposures reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence. However, BAX Global, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: The ocean vessel Horizon Hawk was in route from Oakland, CA to Honolulu, HI when the vessel reported a leak from container MSKU351478 which was loaded with drums of class 8 and class 9 cargo destined to a dry cleaning business.  Chemtrec was notified and guidance was provided on the containment and capture of any spill from the container.  An emergency response contractor was contacted to secure the shipment when the vessel arrived in Honolulu.  The container was diapered offloaded from the vessel under controlled circumstances to avoid any further damage and placed in a secure area.  It was discovered that one drum containing 30 gallons of Potassium Hydroxide, Solution, 8, UN1814 was completely empty.  The contents of the container had leaked through a hole in the drum.  The hole was caused by the drum being creased at the point where it overhung from a wooden pallet.  There was also a small leak from a loose closure on one of the drums.  It was wiped and the closure tightened.  The shipment was secured and reloaded to the vessel.
column169: Drums of cargo must be securely positioned on a pallet where there is no overhang.  An overhang places stresses on a specific point on the bottom of the drum as opposed to the weight being distributed over the base of the drum on a pallet.  Drums should be them securely strapped together to prevent shifting.

column168: On4/5/07 at approximately 1300, container number SUDU 491577 was found leaking.  The shipper (NACA Logistics) contracted a cleanup company (Chemical Detection Services) to conduct the cleanup.  A 55 gallon drum of Tetrakis(Hydromethyl) Phosphonium Sulfate was found leaking.  The drum appears to have been punctured due to human error.  Approximately three gallons spilled.  The spill was cleaned.  The damaged drum was placed in an overpack drum.  All waste was properly disposed of.

column168: On Friday, April 6th at 1440 hours, a CSX Transportation Bennett Yard Car Inspector observed Tank Car DODX14338 (Residue - Last Contained Fuel, Aviation, Turbine Engine) dripping product from the bottom outlet valve area.  CSX Management immediately implemented their emergency response action plan and isolated the area.  The shipper, US Government, was contacted and informed of the release.  CSX contacted emergency reponse contractor, Hepaco Environmental, to respond and secure the car.  Once on site, Hepaco representatives found the cause of the release was due to a torn and deteriorated bottom outlet cap gasket.  At 1630 hours, Hepaco replaced the bottom outlet cap gasket and tightened the closure cap with a wrench. The car was secured and released on to destination.    Cause Code:  580  NARRI:  5 (4+1+0) x (2+0) = 50

Affected railroad tank car (NPCX272) was part of a train when crew observed intermittent gas venting from pressure relief valve. Train was stopped and crews vacated area. Shipper (Lyondell/Equistar) was contacted and dispatched emergency response personnel. Lyondell response team contacted local fire department (Joliet) and emergency response contractor (HMHTTC). Fire department departed scene shortly after their arrival based on discussion with Lyondell personnel and site assessment. Per Lyondell personnel, the outer tank lining failed, which caused product temperature and pressure rise such that relief valve engaged. Subject tank car was flared as a means to control/burn venting. EJ&E personnel located and retrieved empty tank car. Flare was relocated to empty tank car and product transload between tank cars was commenced by HMHTTC. Transload completed approximately 16 hours after initial awareness.

column168: A van trailer operated by Clean Harbors Envirodnmental Services, Inc. was in-transit between the loading point and the destination facility and had stopeed at Clean Harbor's 10-day intrasiit storgae location located at 13351 Scenic Higway in Baton Rouge, LA.  DUring a routine inspection of the van trailer that was parked at a contained concrete loading pad, facility personnel identified liquid material had escaped from a 55 gallon container.  Facility personnel secured the area, retrieved the shippinag papaers and conducted an in-house emergency reposne to collect released material and secure the leaking container.  The container in question was identified and placed into a suitable salvage drum  all clean-up debris generated as a result of the clean-up was placed in this container and sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility,  The floor of the trailer and the concrete dock impacted by the release was decontaminated and placed back in service.
column169: An investigation of this incident found that the container in question was filled with a liquid/solid mixture when, in fact it was described as a solid.  The container in question, when inspected, was found to have evidence of exterior corrosion rust at the bottom chime.  It is believed that during conditions normally incident to transportation that the chime failed allowing the liquid to escape from the container.  In order to prevent a recurrence, we have reviewed with the driver of this vehicle the propoer pre-loading inspection requirement for each container accepted for transportation.  This involves the inspection of container condition, marking, labeling and closure devices. In addition, the driver has been re-isntructed to isnure the material being accetped for transportation matches the material approved for transportation.  Discussions with the shipper indicated that liquid material consistent with the solid material expected was inadvertantly palced in the container.  Steps have been taken to insure that lqquid wastes be placed in appropriate containers on a go forward basis.  PLease note that the capacity of the container listed is an estimate as the container markings were not availabel for review.

DUring a routine inspection, it was discovered that approximately 25 gallons of material had escaped from a 55 gallon plastic drum onto the floor of the trailer and the concrete parking area where the trailer was staged.  Facility personnel reviewed the shipping paper and determined an appropriate response plan based on the material involved.  Using propoer health and safety controls and equipment, a crew entered the trailer and identified the leaking container.  A suitable absorbant material was deployed to absorb all freee liquid and this along with the damamged container was placed in a suitable salvage drum that was subsequently sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.  The van trailer and surrounidng parking are was decontaminated and placed back into service.  It is believed that the material in the container was either experienced an exothermic reaction or the material pressurized in the container causing the side wall of the container to fail.
column169: As indicated in the previous section, it is suspected that the material in question experienced either an exothermic reaction or the material volatized causing a pressure build up that resulted in the drum to fail.  In order to prevent a recurrence, we have expired the waste profile for this material until such time as the shipper determines the root cause of the failure.  Future shipments will not be accepted until this information is provided.  Please note that at the time of loading, the containers were inspected and no visual signs of damage, distortion or leakiage was observed.  Driver and loading personnel will continue to inspect each package as it is loaded and will take appropriate corrective actions should an issue be found.

column14: Exit 49 of I-80 West off ramp
column168: At approximately 10:00 am (MT) on April 16, 2007 a flat-bed trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. (Clean Harbors) experienced a load securement failure which resulted in a release of hazardous waste material from an Intermediate Bulk Container (IBC).  At the time of the release the driver was transporting 44 flexible IBC containers of Incinerator Ash picked up earlier in the morning from Stericycle Inc., incinerator in North Salt Lake City.  The material was being shipped as RQ, Hazardous Waste Solid, N.O.S. (contains lead and cadmium), 9, NA3077, PGIII.   A fiber strap holding the last row of the IBC’s failed and two bags each containing approximately 960 pounds of the incinerator ash  fell  off the flatbed trailer onto the off-ramp of I-215 at the intersection of I-80 West.  One container spilt open upon striking the asphalt roadway releasing it contents while the second container remained intact.  The driver immediately pulled his vehicle oover to the side of the road, deployed the appropriate safety warning devices retireved his shipping papers and notified local  emergency authorities.  In addition, the driver notified his home dispatcher.  Upon notification, an emergency crew was dispatched to the scene.  The shipper of the material was also notified and they sent representatives to the scene to assist in the clean-up.  Upon arrival, local emergency authorities closed the off-ramp to allow the clean-up operation to commence in a safe manner.  All released material was recontainerized and placed in a bulk roll-off container along with all clean-up debris.   At conclusion of the clean-up operation which lasted approximatley four (4) hours, the trailer was released from the scene and continued to its intended destination without incident.  The material involved in the releases was properly containerized and is being sent to a suitable waste management facility.
column169: The investigation conducted in response to this release found that one of the straps used to secure the contianers to the trailer was found to have a ¾ of an inch cut which allowed the strap to fail resulting in the cargo falling off the trailer.  The defect caused the strap to become loose and the cargo to eventually fall off.  At the time of loading, the driver did not identify an issue with the load securement device.  In order to prevent a recurrence of this event, the driver will receive refresher training on proper pre and post trip inspection protocol, en-route load check requirements and proper blocking and bracing techniques.  In addition, all load securement devices on this vehicle will be inspected and any defective or questionable devices will be removed from service and replaced.  The vehicle itself will be fitted with removeable sidewalls desinged to provide a second means of containment and securement to complement the strapping system used to secure this type of shipment in the future.

column168: When the car inspector was doing his routine inspection, he noticed a vapor cloud above this car.  There was also a strong smell.  He reported this to the Yardmaster who in turn reported it to the chief dispatcher.  The chief dispatcher called myself, John Vergis(the Assistant Environmental Officer)and I came out to look at the problem.  Before I left I called the OEPA and the local fire dept.  I also called SunPro, and Environmental contractor that we use. The car in the mean time was safely moved to another location away from people.  When we came out and inspected the car we found that the lid used to fill the car had loose bolts causing the gasket to fail.  We removed the old gasket and installed a new one and tightened down the lid and installed a new seal.  We then moved the car to our fuel pad and washed the car down so it would not be a hazard to others.  The water was collected and treated at our waste water treatment plant.  The car was then released for service.
column169: Employees need to be better trained on the proper securement and inspection of cars before they leave the facility.

column168: A BNSF switch crew reported GATX 10030 with a small product slosh emanating from the manway cover area during normal switching movement in the railyard. The rail movement was immediately stopped. The BNSF Assistant Director Hazardous Materials responded and found the manway securement bolts tool tight. The manway seal (LUBRIZOL 501011) was removed and the securement bolts loosened to check the condition of the manway nozzle gasket. The 20 inch gasket was found to be approximately 90% missing and a new Viton manway gasket was applied. The manway cover was resecured and a BNSF HAZMAT seal numbered 1053 was applied to the manway. Spillage on the tank car shell was cleaned by an application of a bleach solution. No ground impact was evident. No further product release was noted during a subsequent rail movement. Response was concluded by 1450 hrs. CDT, 4/10/07.   It should be noted that GATX 10030 was delivered to the BNSF in error by the PTRA in Houston, TX on 4/05/07 and GATX 10030 was returned to the PTRA at Houston on 4/15/07.

column168: Two 385 gallon steel totes arrived on a trailer from Casper. Upon arrival, it was noticed that the two totes were leaking from the top of the tanks. One tank had product that spilled over the side of the tank and onto the cardboard that was underneath the tank. The cardboard appeared to catch all of the product that spilled. Olympus from Billings was contracted by Nalco to come and clean up the tanks. They found that one of the tanks leaked from the inlet cap and that the cap was nol screwed on completely by the shipper. The second tote leaked through the vents and they said possibly because it had been overfilled. After both totes were cleaned up, Nalco released the shipments to be delivered to the consignee.
column169: Both of the hazardous spills would be a result of shipper error, The first tote did not have the inlet cap screwed completely on and my suggestion would be for the shipper to check the totes again before shipping to avoid this type of spilll. For the second tote I would suggest to watch the amounts when filling to prevent overfilling of the product in the tote.

column168: On 4/23/2007, at 11:15 AM, a subcontracted transporter arrived at Veolia, Sauget, IL facility with a shipment of drums for unloading.  Upon opening the trailer doors it was found that two 55 gallon fiber drums had fallen over during transportation due to improper load securement and were leaking.  The lids were still intact but material was leaking from around the lids and rings.  10 gallons of material leaked onto the trailer floor and into secondary containment.  The material was cleaned up with the appropriate absorbent, packaged and incinerated on-site. There was no release to the environment.
column169: The transporter needs to ensure that the load is properly blocked and braced to prevent the drums from falling over while in transportation.

column168: Driver was preparing to unload product from rail car to the trailer, when he opened the dome lid and smelled a slight odor of ammonia. The driver checked around the pressure relief valve with ph paper, and found that there was a slight leak. He then notified his immediate supervisor at once. It was decided to unload all contents of the rail car into three trailers. At the conclusion of unloading, fleet vendor was dispatched to scene, and preceded to replace the o-rings on the pressure relief valve. This was successful in stopping the leak. 50 pounds of vapor was estimated to have been released. No evacuations were made, No injuries were reported and no complaints of off-site odor were recorded.

column168: Driver had made 4 deliveries when he stopped for lunch. After lunch, driver did walk around inspection prior to departing truck stop.Driver drove approximately 24 miles to customer Riceland Foods. At customer it was discovered that the tote (IBC) body had an 8" crack approximately 3 feet up from the bottom of the tote which had allowed some product to leak from the IBC until the level of the liquid was below  the crack. With the tote no longer leaking, a forklift operator at customer took the  tote off the trailer and unloaded it in their normal process.    We believe the crack in the tote body occurred when the driver drove arcross 2 sets of rought railroad tracks upon entering the delivery location facility. the tote body was secured against a support bracket in nose of the the trailer which may have caused the crack to occur when the tote was shaken while crossing over the rough railroad tracks.
column169: we discussed taking the trailer to shop and having the support bracket modified as well as moving the tote (IBC) off the nose of the trailer through the use of added blocking, bracing and dunnage.

column168: On 04/06/07 at 17:48 hrs., CSXT Trainmaster, Sean McNamara, reported tank car, PROX 41838, load propylene tetramer, leaking liquid from top of car.  The car was isolated and CSXT emergency response contractor, Eagle Construction + Environmental Services, Inc. was contacted to respond. Willard Ohio Fire Department was notified and responded to the scene. Ohio EPA was also notified (Report # 0704-39-1495).  ECESI personnel discovered leak at mounting flange of liquid line valve, to the liquid eduction mounting flange. ECESI noted the gasket for the fitting had deteriorated. ECESI tightened the mounting flange bolts and car was moved to spill pan within CSXT, Willard Terminal and was monitored by ECESI and Willard Ohio Fire Department. ECESI returned on April 19, 2007, and replaced the mounting flange gasket. Specialized Professional Services, Inc. (SPSI), Washington, PA, qualified this fitting in accordance with U. S. DOT Regulations.    Cause Code:  293  NARRI:  5(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 60

column168: During normal switching operations in the railyard, a BNSF switch crew reported GATX 18592 dripping product from its bottom outlet area. GATX 18592 was carefully moved and isolated nearby in the railyard. Containment and absorbent pads were placed under GATX 18592. The BNSF responder reported finding all seals intact and the top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV) partially open. The responder closed the TOBOV 1/4 turn. The bottom outlet cap (BOC) was checked and it had the appearance of being cross-threaded. The responder tightened the BOC slightly to end any further product dripping by 2130 hrs. CDT, 4/14/07. The BOC was not removed. All spillage evaporated. No ground impact was noted.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

Driver reported that he had product transfer hoses hooked up to pump product from cargo tank to customer storage tank but he hadn't started his pump yet.  When he opened valve on trailer, product leaked out of hose connection between 2 hoses going from trailer outlet to pump intake.  Driver said he wasn't sure it was a gasket issue so instead of just replacing the gasket, he replaced the whole section of hose.  He thinks it may have been a problem with the coupler.  He completed the offload with no further incidents.
column169: Driver received remedial training to increase knowledge of coupling inspections.

NRC Environmental Services, Inc. recovered the free product and placed the product into two (2) 55-gallon drums.  The drums were left on the trailer and all product was forwarded to the consignee.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The Material Safety Data Sheet was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was accidental and may have been the result of improper loading, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Werner Enterprises will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: April 3, 2007 at 23:50, five out of 28 lead acid batteries, fell out of a container while being re-positioned within the Cargo ramp area, one of the 5 batteries after impacting the ground began to smolder.     Battery type: Deka Unigy I  Manufacturing: East Penn manufacturing co., inc  MSDS: Valve Regulated Lead Acid Battery  CFR: Battery Non-Spillable 49 CFR 173.159 (d)  Trade Name: Cell; Absorbed Electrolyte, Sealed Valve Regulated Non Spillable Battery    Atlanta Fire and Airport Authorities were contacted to respond in handling of the smoldering battery.  Prior to emergency responses arrival, ChemTrec was contacted to obtain Emergency Response procedures, along with a copy of the MSDS.  Batteries are covered by 2004 Emergency Response Guide 154.    The call to ChemTrec verified/confirmed the batteries were non-regulated according to Section IX of the MSDS, “Other Regulatory Information”, U.S. DOT:  “The Non-Spillable lead acid battery complies with the provision listed in 49CFR173.159(d) therefore must not be marked with an identification number, such as UN2800, or a hazard label, such as corrosive.  Also, having passed IATA/ICAO special provision A67, these batteries are not subject to the air dangerous goods regulations”.  (MSDS attached)    Details surrounding this event are as follows:    ¿  March 28th, DHL tendered a three piece shipment, two pallets of batteries (non Restricted) and one wood crate containing office equipment totaling 5000 lbs. Routing is STL to SJU, Delta Air Waybill number 00613802434 (Shipper Declaration attached)    ¿  STL loaded the shipment on Towne Air Freight truck 028E/28 which makes a stop in BNA then continues on to ATL (Manifest attached)    ¿  Shipment was received in ATL on the 29th @ 11:39 and set up for flight 579/31 to SJU.    ¿  One (wood crate containing office equipment) of the 3 shipments was shipped to SJU on DAL 579 on the 31st.  The other two pallets were unable to make this flight due to space limitations.    ¿  April 2nd,around 11:06 the two pallets of batteries were being staged within the Cargo building for DAL 579 on the 3rd.    ¿  Around 17:00, one of the two pallets while being staged within the cargo yard, prior to being transported to the flight, collapsed, spilling the batteries.  Batteries were restacked and placed within a container (ULD DPN 47305 DL)    ¿  At 23:50, while ULD DPN 47305 DL was being staged within the Cargo yard, 5 batteries fell out of the container, and upon impact with the ground, one of the five batteries began to smolder    ¿  Delta Operation Command Center was notified, along with contact Carina Bertella, Corporate Dangerous Goods.    ¿  Atlanta Fire and Rescue along with Atlanta Operations was contacted for response    ¿  While handling the smoldering battery, the other pallet of batteries contained within ULD DPN 39063 DL was located, removed from staging for DAL 579, April 3rd, secured and quarantined (Photos attached)    ¿  April 3rd, FAA Southern Regional o

column168: Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. had accepted a shipment of hazardous waste for transportation to a licensed waste management facility.  During the course of transportation, the shipment was being temporarily stored at a 10-day transfer faciltiy located at 117 Frontage road in Pacific, WA.  The IBC in question was placed into temporary stroage at the transfer station in question when the bottom valve was inadvertantly struck by the forks of a lift truck.  The damaged resulted in a failure of the bottom valve which allowed approximately 70 gallons of material to be released to the concrete floor of the warehouse.  Facility personnel immediatley positioned the IBC to halt the release of material and initiated clean-up activities.  A suitable absorbent material was used to contain and absorb all free liquid.  The remaining liquid in the IBC was transferred into suitable non-bulk packages.  All clean-up debris, remaining liquids and the damage IBC were then sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.  While the response activites were being conducted, facility personnel contacted the local fire department as a precaution and both the Washington Emergency Management Agency (Report # 07-0959) and the Washington Department of Ecology (Report # ERTS561698) were notified.  A representative from the Washington Department of Ecology contacted facility management to confirm release had been remediated and the clean-up was complete.
column169: In order to prevent a recurrence, representatives form the Company's Health and Safety and Operations Departments conducted refresher fork-lift training.  In additon, a discusiion on proper warehouse management was held highlighting the absolute requirement for exercising due care and caution when conducting all aspects of facility operations.

SPSI changed out the  broken rupture disk with a Zook 165lb.rupture disk.  Car was secured and released to destination. column168: A San Joaquin Valley Railroad (SJVR) transfer crew reported entrained GATX 21230 in their consist at the west end of the BNSF Bakersfield railyard leaking product from the bottom outlet area. The SJVR crew stopped movement and local F.D. responders closed the top operated bottom outlet valve (TOBOV) approximately 1/2 turn. This slowed the release at the top of the threaded bottom outlet cap (BOC) to a slow drip prior to 0930 hrs. PDT, 4/25/07. A receptacle was placed under the BOC to catch the product drips and GATX 21230 was isolated in the railyard. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder relieved the internal pressure within GATX 21230 and carefully removed the BOC. The responder found that the BOC gasket was missing. Consignee representatives furnished a replacement BOC gasket and it was applied within the BOC. After the BOC was tool tightened, no further drippage was noted from the BOC, ending all product release by 1300 hrs. PDT, 4/25/07. A BNSF contractor was summoned to remediate any detectable ground impact spillage.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Missing Component or Device
column168: BNSF mechanical personnel reported GATX 80561 (waiting repair to its draft gear assembly at the repair track) was leaking product from the top valve area and was running down the side shell. A trench was dug in the ground below GATX 80561 to contain the spillage that was starting to pool and a receptacle was placed under GATX 80561 to catch additional product runoff from the side shell. A BNSF contract responder assisting removed the seal from the protective valve housing cover (Seal numbered CGL Blair 0185467) and inspected the valves. The liquid valve handle stem was observed as the leak source. The valve was in the closed position. The liquid valve handle stem was loose (wiggled) to the touch and no packing material was evident around the stem. The responder alleviated the internal pressure within GATX 80561 and then applied packing material around the valve handle stem. After the packing was applied the leak stopped. Seal numbered BNSF 0251318 was applied to the valve housing. Response was concluded by 1400 hrs. CDT, 4/29/07. All spillage evaporated.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: While inspecting the trailer, driver noticed small amount of liquid near rear door. Driver made inspection and determined a small amount of liquid was present on top and down the side of one tote (275 gallons). The contents were a cleaning compound containing sodium hydroxide. The driver called his dispatcher at Marten Transport, who then called Environmental Management, Inc. (E.M.I.), who has a contract to provide nationwide Emergency Response. E.M.I. contacted a local subcontractor, Seneca Environmental Services (Seneca), who responded to the site. The spilled material was cleaned up and the cap was tightened down. There was also a bung in the center of the cap which was also loose. Seneca determined both the bung and the cap had not been properly tightened. This allowed the material to splash against the cap during transit. The tote was inspected and no other problems were observed. Seneca determined all the material had remained inside the trailer, which was cleaned with absorbent material.  The incident took approximately five (5) hours from the call to the dispatcher until the response was completed. It was determined it was “human error” in not tightening the bung and cap on top of the tote. One (1) other tote with the same material was observed and had no problems.

column168: The incident was caused by a highway accident. Vehicle 2 (a tractor-trailer) struck our vehicle (a tractor-trailer) in the in the rear. This caused our vehicle to leave roadway and overturn off the highway. After striking our vehicle in the rear, Vehicle 2 loss control and overturned in the highway causing the road closure. The overturn caused damage to some of the batteries thus the leak took place. These batteries were “spent” and were being transported to be recycled. Many of the batteries contained very little fluid. The batteries were being transported under the packaging exception CFR49 173.159(e). The trailer was not placarded.    A witness of the accident helped our driver from the truck. The NC Highway Patrol was next to arrive, followed by the Linwood NC Fire Department. Neither our driver nor the other vehicle’s driver were seriously injured and required no immediate medical attention. Upon notification we contacted Crawford Wrecker Service to handle the accident cleanup, and A&D Environmental Services was contacted to handle the chemical spill. Next the NC State Emergency Management and the Rowan County Emergency Management were contacted. Later Davidson County Emergency Management was contacted. (The information we first received was that the accident took place in Rowan County NC, later we discovered the accident happened about a ½ mile from the county line and was actually in Davidson County NC.) The next contact was to the National Response Center. The road closure was due the other vehicle blocking the road, not because of the spill.     Our truck came to rest near a creek. Our environmental contracted placed absorbent booms in 3 locations to prevent and capture any of the trucks fuel from contaminating the water. Soda ash was applied to the soil to neutralize the acid from any of the leaking batteries. A vacuum truck was used to remove any contaminated soil from the battery spill and truck fuel spill. Our environmental contractor arrived within a few hours after the accident and took measures to contain any spill. However due the other vehicle blocking the highway and the upside down position of our truck it took some 12 or 14 hours from the time of the accident to completely remove all the batteries from the site. The batteries were reloaded into 2 poly-lined roll-off containers and transported to A & D Environmental’s facility for repackaging.
column169: The spill was a direct result of our truck rolling over after leaving the roadway due to an accident. Considering the event the packaging performed well.

column168: Driver was traveling on Neely Wingard Road toward Gilbert, SC. The driver failed to slow to an appropriate speed before entering a long, sharp, right hand curve, and could not negotiate the turn. The unit proceeded across the oncoming lane and rolled over, coming to rest on the left shoulder of the road.   The trailer was loaded with liquid asphalt. A hole ripped in the left front of the trailer on impact allowed product to leak out of the trailer and onto the ground surrounding the trailer and adjacent areas. All product was retained in an area of approximately 6,000 ft2.  An environmental remediation crew was immediately summoned to the scene and was able to dam up areas of product flow to retain the produce in a relatively small area. Due to the thickness and properties of the product, the spill cooled and set up on top of the ground and was not absorbed into the soil. Cleanup was completed the next day by removing the product from atop the ground and restoring the original grade of the affected property.
column169: APC maintains an excellent safety program, including new driver orientation and regular safety meetings which train drivers in depth on safe driving techniques, including speed and rollover prevention. This program will be maintained with a continued focus on all safety areas. In addition, drivers have been stopped from using the route in which this accident took place because of the dangers of the long and unusual curve on this road.    This road is dangerous for travel in a commercial motor vehicle, and is no stranger to accidents involving such vehicles. Because of the unusual length and radius of the curve in which this accident occurred, and the proximity to water in other areas of this stretch of road, HazMat carrying CMV’s should not use this road for through traffic.

UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING 1 X .184 LITER PLASTIC BOTTLE OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE  SOLUTION. THIS HAD LEAKED DUE TO THE CLOSURE COMING OFF OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLE. ALSO, IN THE SAME PACKAGE WAS .153 LITERS OF ISOPROPANOL SOLUTION, 1.017 LITERS OF ALCOHOLS NOS (2-PROPANOL SOLUTION), AND .255 LITERS OF ACETIC ACID SOLUTION. THESE DID NOT LEAK. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO THE SALT LAKE CITY STATION VIA FLIGHT # 594, N78ODH. THIS SHIPMENT WAS DECLARED AS ISOPROPANOL SOLUTION, CLASS 3, UN1 219, PG II, SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLTION, CLASS 8, UN1824, PG III, ALCOHOLS NOS (2-PROPANOL SOLUTION), CLASS 3, UN 1987, PG III, AND ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, CLASS 8, UN2790, PG III, WITH THE SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED AND ALL THE PROPER  MARKINGS/LABELS. CLEAR OF SCENE: 0101 EST, 04/10/2007.

FILE- 07-191 DOT SHIPPER- ACUITY BRANDS AWB#- RIV 72325401680 BUR  ON 04/11/2007 AT 1148 EST, THE HAZMAT HOTLINE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM THE ORANGE COUNTY STATION, LOCATED AT 2828 JUNIPERO AVENUE, SIGNAL HILL, CA 90755. MIKE FROM THE ORANGE COUNTY STATION REPORTED THAT THEY HAD A LEAKING SHIPMENT. THE HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING 2 X 1 GALLON PLASTIC BOTTLES OF ZEP FORMULA 6556. DUE TO LOOSE  CLOSURES ON BOTH GALLON BOTTLES, A TOTAL OF 24 OZ OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO THE ORANGE COUNTY STATION VIA TRUCK # 11001. THIS SHIPMENT WAS DECLARED AS CORROSIVE LIQUID ACIDIC INORGANIC NOS (HYDROCHLORIC ACID), CLASS 8, UN3264, PG II, WITH THE SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 1559 EST.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: PACKAGE ARRIVED ON FLIGHT 178 FROM MAF ON APRIL 8, 2007.  PACKAGE WAS OFFLOADED AND PUT ON CART AND TAKEN TO CARGO FACILITY.  AS THE CART WAS BEING OFFLOADED, THE CARGO AGENT NOTICED THAT THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING A CLEAR/PINKISH LIQUID.  CORPORATE SAFETY WAS IMMEDIATELY CALLED AND ADVISED AGENT TO DON PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND PLACE LEAKING BOX IN A PLASTIC BAG TO PREVENT MORE CONTAMINATION AND TO ISOLATE THE BOX.  THE CART AND SURROUNDINGS WERE DISINFECTED AS WAS THE AIRCRAFT UPON ARRIVAL IN TULSA.  PRIMARY RECEPTACLE LEAKED AND THERE WAS NO ABSORBENT MATERIALS BETWEEN THE PRIMARY AND SECONDARY MATERIAL.  NO CUSHION MATERIAL WAS PRESENT.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. Driver was delivering diesel to a customer location. Driver was to drop 2450 gallons into a tank that held 13500 gallons. The tank had 41 inches prior to start of drop. As product was dropping it began to back up and leak. The driver immediately shut off flow of product howver the fuel continued to leak after the belly valve was closed. Approximately 40 gallons was spilled into the grass. No product went into drains. The spill was cleaned up by Gaurdian Cleanup & Aqua Clean.
column169: Aqua Clean and Gaurdian both determined that there was a faulty float ball in the system which resulted in mechanical failure causing the spill. The float ball was replaced by Gaurdian.

The lid on the manhole of the tank trailer was not secured properly after loading the tank package.  The oil spilled on top of the tank and eventually spilled out on to the road.  The driver immediatly stopped after recognizing the spilled oil and called our company and local authorities.  Our company sent three representatives for inspection and spill clean up.  Also we contacted our emergency spill response to help clean up the site.  Upon inspection we found no defects on the tank trailer.  The driver did not secure the tank lid correctly.  The estimated loss was approximately 35 gallons.  Our company along with the spill company worked with the police and fire department to clean up all the fuel oil on the road with oil abosorbent.  It is to be noted that the tank was decertified I had to put in a date so I just put the manufacture date but the tank has been decertified!  Please note this!
column169: All of our drivers received a safety bulletin to remind them about securing lids and manholes when top loading a tank trailer.  IN  addition, remedial training will be performed on inspecting lids and manholes before loading and securing them properly after loading.  Loading a tank trailer from the top of the trailer is rarely done anymore.  The trend in the refineries seems to be eliminating top loading of the tanks because of the liabilities involved.  So as refineries continue to get rid of top loading tanks the human error in loading and securing the package is diminished.  The safe functions tied into bottom loading a tank trailer reduces the human error aspect of the package not being secured properly in the tank.

column168: ON OR ABOUT 04/18/07 1300 AFTER HAVING A TIRE REPAIRED, NOTICED A  LIQUID LEAKING FROM MY TRAILER. I CONTACTED MY COMPANY AND MADE THEM AWARE THAT TRUCK 303 PULLING TRL#027697 HAD A HAZMAT SPILL IN THE PARKING LOT OF THE HIGHWAY GARAGE INC. ON 1269 AMERICAN LEGION ROAD FREDERICKSBURG,VA 22405.  I SPOKE WITH  BOTH INDIVIDUALS ABOUT ThE SPILL THEY INFORMED ME THAT THEY WOULD NOTIFY THE SHIPPER CLEAN HARBORS IN BALTIMORE,MD. THAT WE NEEDED SOMEONE TO COME OUT AND CLEAN THE SPILL AND SECURE THE LEAKING PRODUCT. THE LIQUID THAT WAS LEAKING OUT TARNISHED THE DRIVE AXLE RIM ON THE PASSENGER SIDE OF MY TRACTOR AND GAVE OFF A STRONG  CHEMICAL ODOR. A REPRESENTATIVE FROM CLEAN HARBORS HOME OFFICE CALLED ME  BACK ON MY CELL PHONE AND INFORMED ME THAT THEY WERE SENDING A CREW FROM RICHMOND TO DO THE CLEAN UP BUT IT WOULD BE AFTER 1530 BEFORE THEY ARRIVED. I PLACED ABSORBENT PADS UNDERNEATH THE AREA THAT THE LIQUID AS COMING OUT OF THE TRAILER.  I BOUGHT SOME OIL DRY FROM THE HIGHWAY GARAGE AND BUILT A DAM AROUND THE SPILL TO PREVENT THE LIQUID FROM ANY FURTHER SPREADING AND CONTAIN THE SPILL. AFTER WAITING ABOUT AN HOUR I RECEIVED A MESSAGE FROM HIM ASKING ME TO CONTACT THE POLICE.  I ASKED HIM TO VERIFY HIS REQUEST FOR THE POLICE WHICH HE DID AND I REPLIED THAT I WOULD CONTACT THEM.  AFTER THE SHERIFF’S DEPT. WAS NOTIFIED 3 FIRE DEPTS. REPLIED TO THE CALL AND SHUT DOWN ROUTE 1 AND 4 OTHER STREETS IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  THE FIRE DEPT. ASKED ME TO COME WITH THEM AWAY FROM THE TRUCK.  I TOOK OFF MY PPE AND WENT WITH THE FIRE DEPT. ACROSS THE STREET FROM MY TRUCK. AFTER THE CLEAN HARBORS CREW ARRIVED IT TOOK APPROXIMATELY 7 HOURS TO UNLOAD AND CLEAN THE SPILL AND RELOAD THE TRAILER. I HAD SPOKEN WITH 3 DIFFERENT DEPUTIES REGARDING WHAT HAD HAPPENED BUT I WAS CONT.    I WAS APPROACHED BY A 4TH DEPUTY WHO ASKED ME WHO AUTHORIZED ME TO PARK WHERE I WAS PARKED AND I INFORMED HIM THAT I DID BECAUSE I WAS HAVING A TIRE REPLACED.  HE INFORMED ME THAT WHEN THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP HE WAS GOING THROUGH MY TRUCK AND PAPERWORK WITH A FINE TOOTH COMB AND HE WAS GOING TO CITE ME FOR ANY VIOLATIONS THAT HE COULD FIND.  AFTER THE CLEAN-UP HE RETURNED TO THE SCENE AND USED PORTABLE SCALES TO WEIGH THE REAR TANDEMS OF MY TRAILER AND DO A COMPLETE DOT INSPECTION OF MY TRUCK TRAILER AND MY PAPERWORK. HE CITED ME FOR THE HAZMAT SPILL AND BEING OVERAXLE WEIGHT WHICH I CORRECTED AS I WAS NOT OVER GROSS WEIGHT OF 80,000 LBS.  THE DEPUTY TOLD ME THAT I WAS FREE TO LEAVE AND DELIVER MY LOAD TO ITS DESTINATION.   04/25/07
column169: BETTER TRAINED LAW ENFORCEMENT & SAFETY PERSONNEL.  EVALUATE THE PROBLEM, CONTROL & CONTAIN, WITHOUT CAUSING A PANIC OR DRAWING ATTENTION TO THEMSELVES. THE MORE THE PUBLIC KNOWS, THE MORE THEY WANT TO GO SEE WHAT IS HAPPENING AND THIS MEANS MORE PEOPLE AT THE SCENE TO HAVE TO CONTROL & KEEP UP WITH. IF THE FIRST RESPONDERS HAD LOOKED @ THE MANIFEST & WHAT WAS LEAKING PLUS THE DEGREE OF DANGER INVOLVED THERE WOULD HAVE BEEN NO NEED FOR THE HIGHWAY TO SHUT DOWN & THE PUBLIC TO BE PUT IN A PANIC.  SAFETY IS OUR PRIMARY GOAL.  HOW SAFE IS IT TO SHUT THE HIGHWAY DOWN & HAVE PEOPLE TRAPPED ON THE HIGHWAY FOR HRS?

column168: Intermodal container CLHU 371742 was reported leaking an unknown liquid while it was parked in the BNSF intermodal parking lot after its earlier arrival on a BNSF train. BNSF contract responders remediated the spillage on the pavement. CLHU 371742 was carefully moved to a secure area at the containment dock and placed over a bermed visqueen barrier. The contractor responders were then hired by CMA-CGM America to investigate and mitigate the leak source. The shipper contract responders opened CLHU 371742 and reported finding one composite IBC (UN Package Specification 31HA1/Y/9-06/USA/+AA3710/5050/1998/1050L/60kg/100kPa/3-07/3-07) dripping product at the bottom discharge valve at the IBC base. It appeared that the leak source was at the juncture of the valve insertion into the plastic IBC. The remaining product in the leaking IBC was transferred into a suitable IBC. The spillage inside the container was remediated. Afterwards, all IBC's were returned inside CLHU 371742 properly blocked and braced as before. CLHU 371742 was destined for export to Brisbane, Australia via a sailing vessel departing the Los Angeles harbor area.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: The BNSF conductor on an inbound BNSF train reported a vapor release emanating from entrained tank car GATX 57419 (DOT 111A100W5) upon arrival in the railyard. BNSF mechanical and hazardous material responders inspected GATX 57419 finding a small corrosion hole in the tank shell on the right side approximately 3 feet from the top of the tank at mid-tank near the side ladder. Product was seeping from this 1 1/2 inch hole from an apparent interior liner failure.  BNSF contract responders plugged this hole by 0315 hrs. CDT, 4/19/07, using two layers of fiberglass patching material. Product in GATX 57419 was transferred into another suitable tank car by 1530 hrs. CDT, 4/19/07. Afterwards, a neutralizing solution of soda ash and water slurry was pumped into GATX 57419 to neutralize any residue product inside GATX 57419. Spillage captured and on the ground was also neutralized.

column168: Tank car, UTLX 208111, a load of Alcohols, N.O.S., was discovered leaking from the top in CSX Transportation's rail yard in Selkirk, NY.  CSXT Hazardous Material Sentinel, Paul Watson, responded and determined that product was leaking from around the liquid valve mounting pipe nipple.  He relieved the pressure on the car and the product release stopped.  CSXT responded an emergency response contractor, REACT Environmental Services, who inspected the valve and found the pipe dope was dried out and the valve was not completely seated on the liquid line pipe nipple. REACT removed the valve, cleaned the threads and re-installed the valve. The car was staged for 24 hours and no release of product was found. The car was secured for transportation to the consignee.  The Shipper, Golden Grain Energy was notified via CHEMTREC, report number - 2007042000095.  The incident was discussed with representative of Renewable Products.    Cause Code:  282  NARRI:  5 (5+3+0) x (2+0) = 80

At 2349 hrs. on 04/30/07, the PSCC was notified by CSXT Mechanical Foreman, Joe James, tank car PROX 40358, a load of Styrene Monomer, stablized, was discovered leaking. During routine switching operation, the switch crew smelled an odor coming from car. The car was isolated and a CSXT emergency response contractor, SPSI, was dispatched to the scene. The switch crew was taken to the hospital for observation. They were released with no restrictions and returned to work. SPSI found signs of a leak in the area of the manway cover at the hinge. The manway cover was found to be slightly out of position causing the ring gasket on its lid not to completely seal against the tank car manway nozzle. SPSI re-seated the manway in its proper position and pressure tested all tank car valves and fittings to 20 psi with nitrogen. The corrective actions taken were successful in stopping the leak and securing the tank car for shipment. Car was then released to final destination.    Cause Code:  662  NARRI:  2(5+1+0) x (2+0) = 24

column168: Tank car GATX 55689, a load of Potassium Hydroxide, was found leaking from the top of the car during switching operations in CSXT's yard at Mobile, AL. The car was noted leaking liquid from the manway area of the car when moved.  An employee was splashed with product on his cheek and across the nose.  He quickly washed off and declined medical attention and returned to work. The car was isolated and CSXT response contractor, SWS, was dispatched to the scene.  SWS found one eye bolt on the manway cover in the down position and 5 bolts only hand tight.  The gasket was adjusted and the manway bolts secured wrench tight.  The car was cleaned and released to move back to the plant for further inspection.     Cause Code:  200  NARRI:  5 (5+5+0) x (2+0) = 100
column169: No additional comments.

column168: On 4/27/07, CSXT Terminal Trainmaster in Willard, OH, reported tank car GATX 23089, load Hydrochloric Acid, leaking from its top. column168: A BNSF local train enroute to BASF Corporation to spot railcars derailed four tank cars on industry track after traversing a track derail that was unlocked but not removed by the BNSF crew. Two of these tank cars derailed upright and the other two overturned onto their sides sliding down the track embankment. UTLX 42910 (DOT 111A60W7) on its side leaked a small amount of product from the liquid line/valve bottom flange. BNSF contract responders placed a bucket under the leak source to catch the droplets. The flange bolts were tool tightened and UTLX 42910 was uprighted which ended any further product release.  The product in UTLX 42910 will be transferred into another suitable tank car, then UTLX 42910 will be cleaned and purged.

column168: Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. accepted for transportation a shipment of hazardous waste from Indalex West, Inc. located at 4555 Northstar Way in Modesto, CA.  During the loading process, the driver inspected each container and applied the required markings and labels.  Once loaded, the containers were secured within the transport vehicle and the driver departed the shippers location.  The driver proceeded to CLean Harbors 10-day intransit storage location licated at 3201 Evergreen Avenue in West Sacramento, CA.  Upon arrival at this location, the driver identiifed a small amount of liquid at the rear door of the van trailer and identified a mild solvent odor.  The driver immediately spread a suitable absorbent material at the back of the trailer doors and activated the facility's emergency response team.  Using propoer personnel protective equipment, facility personnel entered the trailer and idneitifed a 55 gallon container that had developed a small pinhole leak on the side of the container.  It is estimated that approximately 9 gallons of material escaped from the container onto the floor of the van trailer.  The container was placed into a suitable salvage drum and all liquid absorbed using an absorbent material.  The clean-up debris and absorbent material was placed in the salvage drum and sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: IN order to prevent a recurrence, drivers will continue to inspect each container as it is loaded and will work to identify those containers whose structutal integrity appears to be compromised.

HE NOTIFIED THE YARDMASTER, AND WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL. THE YARDMASTER THEN NOTIFIED THE NEW ORLEANS FIRE DEPT., NEW ORLENAS POLICE DEPT., HARBOR POLICE, AND THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OFFICE. THE N.O.F.D. AND N.O.P.D. ARRIVED AT 0415. THE GASKET WAS CHANGED, AND THE CAR WAS DECONTAMINATED, WITH A CITRIC ACID SOLUTION, AND RINSED. DECINTAMINATION WAS CONFIRMED USING PH PAPER, THE CAR WAS RELEASED BACK TO THE RAILROAD FOR MOVEMENT. THE HELPER THAT WAS SPRAYED WITH THE CHEMICAL, WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FROM THE HOSPITAL. THE STATE POLICE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED OF THE EVENTS AT 0708, AND INCIDENT # 07-01879 WAS CLOSED OUT NY THEIR OFFICE.

column168: Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. accepted a shipment of hazardous waste for transportation i a cargo tank motor vehicle.  During the normal course of transportation, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbors 10-day intransit storage facility located at 3201 Evergreeen Avenue, West Sacramento, CA.  After secring the vehicle and conducting a ppost trip inspection, the driver was released from duty.  Subsequent to the driver leaving the office for the day, facility personnel identified a minor release of product from the exhaust pipe of the cargo tank's scrubber unit.  The individual placed a contaimnet pail under the exhaust pipe and deployed a suitable absorbent material over the area where the release occurred.  It is estimated that 6 gallons of material escaped and was either contained within the containment pail or was absorbed with the absorbent material.  Once identified, facility personnel contacted local police and fire as well as the California Toxic Substance Control Department.  Authorization was obtained to conduct a truck to truck transfer for the leaking container to an alternate cargo tank.  This operation was done without incident. Once transferred, the shipment was sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.  IN addition, all clean-up debris was containerized and disposed of in accordnace with all applicable Federal and State requirements.  An inspection of the cargo tank that failed identified a travel valve that would not close completely.  This ank was placed out of service pending repairs and follow-up inspections.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: On April 20th, 2007 a Consumers Energy stake truck dispatched to an electrical substation at 27780 Blue Star Highway, Covert, Michigan.  While on site, the truck was loaded with 52 lead acid batteries on wood pallets.  Each battery contained 6.4 gallons electrolyte (sulfuric acid).  The batteries were strapped together using duct tape and nylon tie downs.  The batteries were not directly strapped to the pallets.  The pallets were not secured to the vehicle.  Neither placards not a shipping paper were provided to the driver, who accepted the load and proceeded to Consumer's Jackson Service Center, 1955 West Parnall, Jackson, Michigan.    During transport, the driver experienced an incident which forced a sudden brake application near the Capitol Avenue on-ramp to Interstate 94 near Battle Creek.  At this time, there was a load shift.  Some batteries tipped at this time.  The driver visually checked his load, did not stop, and continued to the Jackson Service Center.    Upon arrival at the Jackson Service Center, leaking sulfuric acid was observed.  Of the 52 batteries shipped, 4 were empty, and 18 showed evidence of minor leaking.  Staining was observed on the stake truck's wood floor.  The leaks were caused by inverted batteries draining fluid out the top vent hole.  Consumers Energy personnel contained the leak, and contacted an environmental contractor to neutralize the release and clean the batteries.  The stake truck bed and other affected areas were decontaminated by Consumers Energy personnel using power washing / rinse.    This report contains a release volume in solid pounds.  The release was, in actuality, 25 liquid gallons of sulfuric acid.  The "solid pound" entry was required due to the Incident Report Systems' inability to allow battery, wet, filled with acid releases in liquid terms.  We used the shorthand of 10 lbs per gallon of sulfuric acid for the calculation.
column169: The incident is being addressed on three levels.  First, the issue was addressed with the driver involved in the incident.  Second, the work unit handling battery shipments received several initiatives.  Finally, company wide processes are being reviewed to prevent recurrence.    Several initiatives have been directed toward the driver.  A formal reprimand has been initiated for his role in accepting the hazardous materials shipment.  The driver will be responsible for conducting a safety meeting for other employees, regarding hazardous materials and proper load securement.  The driver also participated in the work unit initiatives listed below.    The work unit involved in battery transport conducted a meeting to review the incident, and discussed several items.  A Company hazardous materials shipping paper, detailing hazardous materials encountered by this work group, was reviewed to assist in identification of regulated materials.  A general review of the hazardous materials regulations and proper load securement was conducted.  The USDOT Guide for Preparing Shipping Papers was reviewed, to further help identify undeclared shipments.  Finally, the battery packaging requirements at 49 CFR 173.59 were specifically reviewed.      Further initiatives are planned for the work group.  An annual review of applicable hazardous materials regulations is planned.  Additionally, Consumers Energy has contacted the Michigan Center for Truck Safety for presentation of a session on Hazardous Materials Training and Load Securement, to provide an independent voice in our program.    Finally, the incident has been reviewed on a corporate level.  Mr. G. Nick Reichert, Fleet Acquisition, Regulatory, and Technical Manager, has reviewed the incident.  Consumers Energy intends to use the knowledge from this incident to strengthen programs across all work areas.  Mr. Reichert also serves as an additional contact for this report, as follows:    Mr. G. Nick Reichert, Fleet Acquisition, Regulatory, and Technical Manager  Consumers Energy, One Energy Plaza, Jackson, Michigan 49201  Office:  517-768-7338  Cell:  517-243-3918  Pager:  517-228-2234  Email:  gnreichert@cmsenergy.com

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While trans-loading from a rail car into a tank at the Sand Springs Railway in Sand Springs, Oklahoma there was a release of approximately 380 gallons of ferrous chloride.  Apparently, the hose from the rail car came out of the tank that was being filled, during the trans-loading process.  Kemira Logistics, Inc. personnel plugged a nearby storm drain that was impacted by the free product, and constructed a dirt berm in an attempt to contain the free liquid.  Sooner Emergency Services, Inc. of Tulsa, Oklahoma was dispatched to perform the remainder of the cleanup.  Sooner Emergency Services, Inc used a vacuum truck to recover as much free liquid as possible and excavated the contaminated soil as needed.  Sooner Emergency Services, Inc. will coordinate disposal of the waste generated as a result of the incident.  No injuries or exposures were reported.
column169: Since the release was accidental any may have been related to a loose hose, no actions have been taken to prevent recurrence.  However, Kemira Logistics, Inc. will continue to reinforce safety guidelines and handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: At 1447 an AUC employee Tommy Smith reported a leak from the bottom of the rail car spraying 5 to 15 feet. Opened the air valve to release pressure and slow leak. Pulled Caustic out through piping into a storage tank. Laid sodium bicarbonate and sand bags to stop flow. By 1452 leak had slowed. Leak was determined to come from flange area connecting internal valve & outlet piping to rail car. AUC employee Les Dodd closedinternal valve and leak stopped with in 15 seconds. Continued to dike flow and 40 cases of pool acid was applied during the neutralization process. Continued to pump caustic into 55 gallon drums. Estimated leak time 15 minutes. By 1523 local EMA and fire departments arrived. At 1645 rail representative Bob Pew arrived to repair gasket on bottom of car. At 1900 he indicated that the rubber gasket used (EPDM) was OK with caustic but was soft and recommended a Gylon 3510 as replacement. He also indicated the the bolts seem to be only hand tight. At 2040 dumpsters arrived to load contaminated soil. Clean up continued through the morning of 05/04/2007 under the directions of AUC Management, with the approval of Scott Coburn with GA DNR and Marian County Environmental agency. Local Fire & Police responded but not report numbers available at this time.
column169: A) Higher level inspections of Westlake rail cars  B) Rail industry and gov't recommend use of harder Gylon 3510 gasket over the EPDM softer ones.

column168: While at Brewer Science, driver was moving a pallet that contained four drums of Muriatic Acid with an electric pallet jack. The pallet he was moving had irregular shape with overhanging boards. One of those overhanging boards caught a drum of Muriatic Acid on a pallet along side of the one he was moving and tore a hole in it. The puncture was approximately 1 1/2 to 2 long and about 2H from the bottom of the drum. Fumes from the Muriatic Acid began to fill the dock area. The Rolla Fire Department was called and they called their Haz—Mat Team. They put lime on the acid to neutralize it and then flushed it with water. The warehouse was evacuated from about   1:45 PM — 5:15 PM.
column169: Instructed the driver on being more cautious and to use more care when moving pallets of freight from the trailer due to potential shifting while in transit.

column25: Potter Oil and Tire Co., Inc.
column168: The release occurred during the transfer of No. 2 Fuel oil from a tanker truck to a customer bulk tank when the customer tank was overfilled. Human error was the cause of the release which was 99% contained in the concrete berm surrounding the bulk tank.  ACTION TAKEN: The driver of the transport truck immediately closed the truck valve and the release stopped. RELEASE RECOVERY AND CLEANUP: The No. 2 Fuel Oil was removed from the berm by vacuum truck and transported to a permitted Used Oil Facility on the customer site.
column169: Customer Preventive measures implemented: (1)Facility SOP revised to provide for strapping of tank prior to filling.(2)Tank to be considered full at 80%.(3)Tank level indicator to be replaced and calibrated.(4)Install high level alarm (audible and visible).(5)Tank design of truck unloading controls to be reviewed, and (6)Meet with facility management to discuss unloading procedures.  Driver has been informed of changes at customer facility.

column168: DRIVER STEVE DIECKEY NOTICED A PAINT SMELL IN HIS TRAILER WHILE DELIVERING. UPON HIS INVESTIGATION HE FOUND THE ABOUVE MENTIONED SHIPMENT WAS LEAKING. THE DRIVER PULLED OUT THE LEAKING FREIGHT AND BEGAN UNSTACKING THE TWO SKIDS OF PAINT WHICH CONTAINED 64 BOXES. AS HE OPENED THE BOXES HE NOTICED SOME OF THE PAINT CANS HAD LOOSE TOPS OR TOPS OPEN. STEVE FOUND THE BOX THAT WAS LEAKING AND THE TOPS WERE OPEN ON THESE CANS AS WELL. THESE WERE ONE GALLON PAILS OF PAINT. ESTIMATED DURATION OF LEAK WAS TEN MINUTES. STEVE STOPPED AT A FARMERS COOP SUPPLY AND BOUGHT ENOUGH ABSORBANT TO CONTAIN THE SPILL IN HIS TRAILER. UPON RETURN TO SERVICE CENTER STEVE AND SERVICE CENTER MANAGER JOHN BOWEN CLEANED UP ALL ABSORBENT AND PLACE LEAKING PAILS AND USED ABSORBENT IN SALVAGE DRUM.

column25: HERITAGE OPERATING L.P. DBA METROLIFT PROPANE
column168: Our customer contacted our local district office in Miami, FL as they thought one of the composite forklift cylinder we supplied them was leaking. Our manager arrived at the scene, took possession of the cylinder and returned it to our office. Our manager found that the cylinder was in fact leaking at the seam where the two halves of the composite cylinder are joined. He isolated the cylinder in a remote area within the confines of our facility. The cylinder was approximately half full at that time. Later the cylinder completely failed by separating into two pieces. Within a short period of time, we had 4 more composite cylinders fail in the same manner.
column169: All composite cylinders we have purchased have been retrieved from our customers’ locations. They have been evacuated of all hazardous material (propane) and purged with nitrogen to completely remove any propane residue. All cylinders except the ones returned to The Lite Cylinder Company have been totally taken out of service and are being stored on our premises. We have replaced these cylinders for our customers’ use with the DOT 4E240 aluminum cylinders approved by DOT.

column168: When unloading trailer 311-6556, after taking out a piece of dunnage in front of two pallets of pails of paint, the unloader noticed that there was paint on the clear shrink wrap and paint pooling around the top of one of the bottom pails on the pallet. The pails were stacked two pails high so when first looking at it, we thought either the bottom of the top pail or the top of the bottom pail was leaking. After we removed the top pail to verify what was leaking, we noticed that at the back side of the pail that we couldn’t see was several dents in the pail which caused the paint to leak out from a crack in the top of the pail. The paint on the back side was already dry indictating the damage occurred before arving at Billings. The loader of the shipment was from UDV and the cause of the damage would be loader error and improper handling of the freight causing it to be damaged and paint to leak out.
column169: To prevent recurrence, I would suggest additional training on loading for the driver from UDV. I would also review the procedures of handling the hazardous materials freight and what to do when there is a leak and pull out the freight as soon as it is noticed that it is damaged.

column168: While unloading trailer 567-6163, a piece of plywood was removed that was in front of two pallets of pails of paint. It was noticed right away that one pail had leaked previously and had pain that dripped down the side of the pail and on the shrink wrap. The side of the pail was dented in and the paint spilled out from the gap in the lid. The paint on the pail and shrink wrap was dry when it arrived. The shipment did have dunnage around it however the leak would be obvious to the laod and since there is no exception at UDV, the spill would be the fault of the loader who mishandled the haz mat freight at UDV. Approximately two ounces was released and the dent in the can was approximately 4 inches long. There was no additional cleanup of the freight except to put the leaking pail in a salvage drum in Billings since the paint that had spilled out was already dry.
column169: To prevent recurrence, I would suggest more training for the loader at UDV on how to properly handle haz mat freight and prevent damaging the product while handling it. It is unknown if this occurred when using a forklift or a pallet jack but either way additional training with these loading tools could prevent another occurrence of this situation.

column168: The driver arrived at the facility, positioned the truck to unload, set the brakes, got out of the truck, and hooked up the hoses to the riser. After approximately five minutes of unloading the anhydrous ammonia, the hose ruptured and a release of product occurred. Immediately after the release, emergency responders were called. The release prevented the driver from activating the emergency shut-off controls, so the driver and a facility employee immediately ran to warn others and began evacuating the neighbors. The emergency responders arrived on scene and the state police continued the evacuation and dosed roads. After the release ended, the authorities permitted facility employees and neighbors to return to the facility and their homes.

On 04/24/2007, CSX Transportation Hazardous Materials Manager, S.Michael Austin, was notified of a derailment in the CSXT Curtis Bay Yard. it was reported that tank car ACFX2200I8, a load of ammonia anhydrous, was derailed and on its side. CSXT Haz-Mat Manager along with the Baltimore City Fire Department envisaged and it was determined that the tank car was leaning at the 1:00 position with the trucks out from under the A end of the car. There was no product release. During rerailing operations the Baltimore City Fire Department decided to evacuate two business near the derailment. The two business that were effected: Arundel Corp Brooklyn Plant moved 4 employees to another part of there facility. Vallerle Trailer & Container Leasing evacuated 2 employees. Once the car was safely rerailed the business were allowed to return to normal operations. The car was inspected and determined that there was no hazmat exemptions noted.
column169: no additional comments.

column168: DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS THE EMPLOYEE FOUND A SMALL LEAK OF MATERIAL AROUND THE TOP OF A SUPERSAK. FURTHER INVESTIGATION DETERMINED THAT SOME OF THE PRODUCT LEAKED FROM AROUND THE FILL HOLE IN THE BAG. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP AND THE BAG CONTINUED ONTO THE CUSTOMER. THE LEAK SEEMS TO HAVE OCCURED DUE A HEAVIER SKID PLACED ON TOP OF ONE OF THE SAKS WHICH CAUSED IT TO SHIFT TO THE SIDE, LOWERING THE FILL HOLE BELOW THE LEVEL OF THE BAG
column169: A CONTINUED EDUCATION PROGRAM TO HELP ENSURE PROPER LOADING PRACTICES. A REINTRODUCTION OF THE PRACTICE OF USING DUNNAGE TO BLOCK AND BRACE FREIGHT. SUPERVISORS INVOVLEMENT DURING THE ENTIRE LOADING PROCESS TO HELP ENSURE THE FREIGHT WILL ARRIVE AT THE DESTINATION IN A SAFE MANNER. A FOCUS ON PROPER EQUIPMENT USAGES (FORKLIFT) SO THAT THE AWARENESS LEVEL FOR THE LOCATION AND LENGTH OF THE FORKLIFT BLADES IS CONSTANTLY ENFORCED.

column58: Bolts or Nuts; Gasket; Manway or Dome Cover
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Misaligned Material, Component, or Device
column168: At O9l4 hrs on 4-9-07, Frank Lerch, Manager Hazardous Materials was contacted by the RMCC, and advised that Kevin McCown, Manager Yard Operations, reported loaded tank car PLCX 221048 leaking. Tank car was located in Lloyd Yard, track 16, Spring, TX, Mile Post 214.46 of the Palestine Subdivision. He further advised there were no drains, waterways or reported exposures resulting from this release. Upon being notified, Mgr. Lerch responded, and requested the RMCC make shipper notification via Chem-Trec.  On arrival and inspection of the car, Mgr. Lerch noted the manway gasket to be misaligned on the manway nozzle, the gasket was worn, cracked, and in poor condition. Additionally, two of the manway swing bolts were in position, but not wrench tight.  Mgr. Lerch replaced the worn gasket with a temporary Gortex gasket. He then secured the car, and released Ito continue onto destination without further incident. There was no clean-up due to the product evaporating upon contact with the atmosphere.    At approximately l33Ohrsthe shipper, Advanced Aromatics was contacted. Mgr. Lerch spoke to John Faulkner, Customer Services Logistic Manager, and advised him of the condition of the car, and corrective actions taken.  Original manway seal # Sealed-36298, replaced with UPRR  CTS-0008781.  PART Ill - PACKING INFORMATION: Question 25. (continuted):  3. What Failed: 121 137 How Failed: 308 Causes of Failure: 510
column169: Proper pre and post inspection of the car prior 10 releasing for transportation.

column168: On April 16th, 2007 Bulktainer UPTU 530033 was reported to be leaking product from its bottom outlet valve. Upon further inspection, Mark Maday, Mgr - Hazardous Materials Management, determined that the gasket between the valve and the tank had failed and that a slow drip had developed. Absorbent material was placed under the container to absorb any further drips pending transfer to another container. On Wednesday April 18th, the load was transfered to container UPTU 660083 and released for continued transportation. Container UPTU 530033 was released to Bulktainer Services for movement to a repair facility.

Gordon Haltdin, Foreman General, notified Lane A. Sekavec, Manager Hazardous Materials, that NS :201 350 was found in 18th Street Yard, Kansas City, KS, with a damaged Super Sack.  The SuperSack was filled with lead concentrate and was loaded into a  gondola with several other Super Sacks. During transportation, a pipe retaining the sacks in an upright position was dislodged and the sack fell over, apparently being torn open by a broken weld from the pipe, allowing some of the contents to release into the bottom of the gondola.  Mr. Sekavec made contact with Horsehead (Shipper) and they dispatched Bellon Environmental (Contractor) to secure the sack, remediate the inside of the gondola and retarp the car. Bellon personnel placed the material in the gondola into two salvage drums to continue in transportation. No other temediation was needed as there was no release of the contents outside the gondola.

column168: Jason Everidge, Car Foreman, reported Tankcar PROX 40842 was releasing product at the Ney Yard in Fort Worth, TX. Mr. Everidge stated there were no injuries involved or waterways affected. Blake Woodson, Manager of Terminal Operations, stated the product was being released from a pipe on the bottom of the tankcar. Michael Moore, Manager of Hazardous Materials, was notified and responded. State and federal notifications were made. At 6:25 PM, Mgr. Moore advised that released product had evaporated prior to reaching the ground and remediation was not necessary. Mr. Moore stated the product released from the liquied eduction valve due to valve not being closed and plug not tool tight.The valve was closed and the plug was secured. Mr. Moore stated the tankcar was released to destination . At 6:34 PM, Mark Thompson, Logistics Manager for Pro Vista - Amazing Energy, was notified of the problem and actions taken to secure the tank car.

column168: Vehicle #1 was traveling north on GA 333. Vehicle #1 was entering a left curve in the roadway and Vehicle #1’s right tires traveled onto the east shoulder of GA 333. Vehicle #1 traveled approximately 284 feet, straddling the right log line of G 333. The driver of vehicle #1 overcorrected left and vehicle #1 traveled approximately 146 feet from the east shoulder to the southbound lane of GA 333. The driver of vehicle #. over-corrected right and vehicle #1 overturned in the Southbound lane of GA 333 and came to final rest on its top, on the west shoulder of GA 333 facing northeast. Vehicle #1 caught flre and released its load onto the roadway. Vehicle #1 was carrying approximately 2500 gallons of diesel and gasoline.   NOTE: The driver of vehicle #1 at first stated that a tire blew out on the vehicle He later stated that the steering had a defect that caused him to lose control of the vehicle. There was no evidence on the roadway indicating tire failure or steering failure. Vehicle #1 negotiated several sharp curves on GA 333 prior to the curve that the crash occurred in.     CITATIONS-VEHICLE #1: DUI COMMERCIAL VEHICLE 40-6-391 (1).  FAILURE TO MAINTAIN LANE 40-6-48, SEATBELT VIOLATION 40-8-76.1

The operator for some unknown reason left the roadway, and while attempting to return back to the paved surface the rear trailer rolled spilling approximately 700 LBS of Ammonium Nitrate Fertilizer. The hazardous material leaked from a diminutive hole about three inches diameter in the rear of our bulk pneumatic cargo trailer and was contained within the barrow ditch. No water sources exist within that area and B & G Roustabout Service was retained to clean up the site. This accident was investigated by the Montana Highway Patrol.

column169: DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF DRUMS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. column168: Lorretta, Jefferson City Police Department, reported a citizen contacted their 911 Center advised a liquid chemical was leaking oul of the top of a railcar at Jefferson and Capifal Streets. This is at Mile Post 124.82 of the Jefferson City Subdivision, in Jefferson City, MO. Jefferson City Police, further advised the Fire Department and Hazmal Team were on location. No waterways were effected, no injuries were reported. John Miller, Manager Environmental Field Operations, was notilied and responded. At 06:22 PM, Loretta, Jefferson City Police bepartment, reported Tankcar TEIX 30000 was the raitcar involved, and material was releasing at the top portion of the railcar. Miller reported upon his recommendation, the hazmat team had stopped the material release and were waiting his arrival. Mr. Miller further advised the material released was contained and no material came in contact with the ground. At 11:58 PM, Miller stated he tightened and secured the liquid valve that was loose on top of the tank car. The tank car was released to transportation.

column168: Mike Winter, Car Foreman, reported Tankcar GATX 45085, on track 21 in yard ten, releasing an unknown amount of material from the top of the tankcar within the East Railyard in San Antonio, TX. Paul Person, Manager of Environmental Field Operations, was notified and responded. At 10:26 PM, Person stated the release was due to a faulty plastic housing around the man way gasket. Mr. Person stated he would replace the gasket. Mr. Person advised that no material reached the ballast or other surfaces. State and federal notifications were issued. At 11:35 PM, Person advised he replaced the rupture disk on Tankcar GATX 45085. Mr. Person further advised he would be meeting with Hazcar Company to disassemble the rupture disk housing and replace it in the morning.

column168: While enroute to Murphy, North Carolina the JAT Oil driver got his rear right tandems over the white line and was unable to recover. As there is very little shoulder before the steep embankment to the river, the loaded cargo tank shifted and rolled the tanker over the bank onto its top only stopping after hitting a tree,. The first two compartments were split open and were the major cause of the release. Local emergency management were first responders to the incident and were able to get hard river boom into the water soon after the wreck, and subsequent release of fuel. JAT Oil was contacted and an OSRO was dispatched Holes were drilled into the side of the trailer, remaining product was recovered, and the unit hauled off. Remediation of the site then commenced.
column169: Highway 64 East and West through the Ocoee Gorge, a dangerous section of road. There have been many car and truck wrecks and fatalities on this route over the years. There are sections where there is little or no flat shoulder on the river side and rocks protrude out to the white line on the mountain or west-bound side. A guard rail would have prevented the accident. Signs instructing “no shoulder ahead” or several areas with flashing caution lights would help. On an operational side the company will dramatically reduce or eliminate altogether traveling this highway.

column169: DRUMS OF CHEMICALS AND OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. CHEDK THE FLOOR OF TRAILER TO ENSURE THERE ARE NO FOREIGN OBJECTS, NAILS OR PIECES OF WOOD PROTRUDING. RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE  PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: I WAS CALLED BY JCI DRIVER GEORGE SEARS.  HE REPORTED HE WAS UNLOADING AT NALCO IN VANCOUVER, WA.  HE SAID THE FORKLIFT DRIVER UNLOADED AND DOUBLE STACKED 7-8 (3800) LB TOTES.  ON THE 8TH TO 9TH TOTE, THE OPERATOR NOTICED APPROXIMATELY 2 CUPS OF UNKNOWN LIQUID.  THE OPERATOR QUARANTINED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS SAFETY SUPERVISOR.  ONCE OFF THE PHONE WITH MY DRIVER. I CALLED NALCO TO FIND OUT THE SITUATION.  LORI TOOK THE CALL. SHE REPORTED SHE HAD USED A PH TAPE TO TEST THE LIQUID, IT SHOWED TRACE AMOUNTS OF ALKALINITY.  I ASKED IF THE TAPE WAS BLEACHED WHITE.  SHE SAID IT WAS SHOWING COLOR FOR ALKALINITY.  I DETERMINED THE LIQUID TO BE RAINWATER.  DURING MY INSPECTION I SAW NO EVIDENCE OR CAPOR GASKET FAILURE.  OUT OT THE TWELVE TOTES, I SAW EVIDENCE OF ONE VENT BUBBLING. NO LIQUID WENT BEYOND THE EVENT.  NALCO USED PAPER TOWELS TO CLEAN UP.  NO SIGNS OF COLORATION OR HEAT WERE GENERATED WITH THE USE OF PAPER TOWELS.
column169: I PERSONALLY DROVE TO THE SITE AND INSPECTED THE SITUATION WITH  OF JCI.  THE ONLY SOLUTION WE CAN CONCLUDE IT TO MAKE SURE ALL RAINWATER IS BLOWN OFF THE TOTES BEFORE SHIPMENTS.  ESPECIALLY, BETWEEN THE BASE AND TOP OF THE TOTE WHERE RAINWATER GETS TRAPPED AND HAS NO MEANS OF COMPLETELY ESCAPING.  BLOWING WITH HIGH AIR PRESSURE SHOULD DRY THIS AREA THOROUGHLY.

column168: Our driver was delivering Low Sulfur Diesel to 2580 BOB Myers St, Hamilton, Ohio.  When he arrived to the location to unload the diesel, he located the above ground tank and check the measuring tape on the side of the tank. It showed that there was 2 Feet of product in the above ground tank. He hooked up his hoses and started to pump of his fuel when fuel started to overflow out of the top of the tank. Approximately 150 gallons. The size of the above ground tank was 5000 gallons capacity.    After the driver shut off his pump and put diapers and oil dry down to start cleaning up spill and contacting dispatch and safety manager he talked to the manager on duty and he was told there was an earlier delivery in the day and after checking the tape measurer on the side of the tank. He detrmind that the tape was stuck and it did not show the gallons that where delivered earlier. Also the shut off valve on the tank did not work.    The safety manager, called Clean Harbors to have a clean up crew come and clean up fuel spill, washed down the concrete and dispose of clean up material.
column169: The changes that where discussed among drivers and safety manager where to make sure to make contact with someone on site if possible to make sure the bulk tank they are unloading into is able to hold the product and all pipes, valves, gauges are in good working order.
