column169: DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING OF BOTTLES, PAILS AND OR DRUMS CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. LIDS AND OTHER CLOSURES MUST BE TIGHT TO PREVENT LIDS FROM LOOSENING, RELEASING THE LIQUID. THE DURABILITY OF THE BOTTLES MUST BE ABLE TO MAINTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS TO PREVENT PACKAGE DETERIORATION. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURED AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER, PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISUCSS WITH SHIPPER ON PROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-INSTRUMENTS OR ARTICLES
column168: On July 18, 2007, Energy Northwest discovered that an undeclared shipment of radioactive material had occurred. During a biannual inventory of radioactive sources at  Columbia Generating Station (Columbia) it was discovered that two EntryScan®  Explosive Detectors, each containing a 10 mCi Nickel-63 source, were transferred to PPL  Susquehanna, LLC without marking the shipment as UN291 1 as required by 49 CFR  173.421(a). The explosive detectors were shipped from Richland, WA on April 13, 2007  via Landstar and received in Berwick, PA on April 17, 2007. Energy Northwest has  confirmed that the devices are currently under the control of an entity licensed to possess  such material.  Energy Northwest purchased the explosive detectors from the manufacturer Ion Track  Instruments in 2002. The detectors arrived at Energy Northwest on September 28, 2002  as Radioactive Material, Excepted Package, Instruments or Articles, 7, UN291 0 which  was the appropriate designation at that time. The received crates were not physically  marked as UN2910 as this was not required by Federal Regulations in 2002. The  detectors were not removed from their original crates and placed in the station  warehouse until they were sold to PPL Susquehanna, LLC in 2007. The explosive  detectors were maintained by Radiation Protection on the station source inventory list;  however, warehouse personnel processing the shipment were unaware that the detectors  contained radioactive material. The explosive detectors were shipped in their original  crates which were not physically denoted as containing hazardous material. Based on  Federal Regulations at the time of the shipment, the explosive detectors should have  been shipped as Radioactive Material, Excepted Package, Instruments or Articles, 7,  UN291 I with the crates labeled UN291 1.  The explosive detectors are maintained under a general license subject to the requirements of 10 CFR 31 and Department of Transportation regulations in 49 CFR. Following identification of the undeclared shipment, Energy Northwest initiated an apparent cause evaluation of the circumstances surrounding the shipment. This incident directly resulted from a lack of clear identification alerting warehouse personnel that the crates contained hazardous material prior to shipment. This condition is attributed to a less-than-adequate understanding of the regulations governing these explosive detectors by all responsible stewards. Had more robust corporate processes governing the control of generally licensed devices been implemented through training, procedures, and oversight, this incident would likely not have occurred.  There were no consequences associated with this event. The sources were checked for leaks upon arrival at PPL Susquehanna, LLC and confirmed less than detectable levels of radioactivity. Furthermore, Nickel-63 is a low activity isotope and during radioactive decay emits a beta-particle that is easily shielded. With these sources contained
column169: Energy Northwest has evaluated the cause of this event and is taking the necessary steps within our corrective action program to prevent recurrence. This incident has  attributed to less-than-adequate processes governing the control of generally licensed devices. As such, Energy Northwest will enhance formal processes governing these devices. These processes will be implemented through enhanced training, procedures, and oversight to ensure consistent compliance with applicable regulations. Furthermore, Energy Northwest will appoint an individual for each licensed device to ensure day-to-day compliance with appropriate regulations and requirements as stipulated in 10 CFR 31.5(c)(12). Each generally licensed device associated with Columbia will be clearly identified to inform station personnel of the device’s controlled status and appointed custodian.

column168: Our driver was delivering material to the consignee via a rear unload trailer with a rear mounted trailer pump. our driver had paperwork signed bu the consignee stating that their storage tank could hold the product shipped. as our driver was pumpimg he was told to stop by plant operator. our driver stopped the pump. the operator came back to our driver and said that their tank was full and that thay had to pump it down. our driver then shut all trailer valves and shut off the truck. He then sat in the truck and called his dispatcher. the operator came back to the  driver and informed him that he had a spill. apparently when the operator started to pump dawn their tank they failed to close a valve and the back pressure parted carriers hose from the end coupling creating the spill.
column169: in our view the driver did nothing to contibute to the spill he was told to shut down and he did. all valves on the trailer were closed. the pump was shut down as well as the tractor engine. The incident was the result of consignee operator error.

column168: FILE-07-36 DOT & OMC     SHIPPER-1977 MOPEDS     AWB#- BTL 20847956452 SAN     ON 04/09/2007 AT 0525 EST, THE HAZMAT HOTLINE RECEIVED A PHONE CALL FROM THE RIVERSIDE COUNTY REGIONAL HUB, LOCATED AT 17101 HEACOCK STREET, MORENO VALLEY, CA 92551. THE RIVERSIDE COUNTY REGIONAL HUB REPORTED THAT THEY HAD AN ODOROUS SHIPMENT OF GASOLINE. THE HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH SHRINK WRAP CONTAINING A GAS POWERED MOTOR BIKE, LEAKING GAS AND OIL. DUE TO THE SHIPMENT NOT BEING DRAINED OF FLUIDS AND IMPROPER PREPARATION FOR TRANSPORTATION, A TOTAL OF 2 OZ OF THE GAS PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO THE RIVERSIDE COUNTY REGIONAL HUB VIA TRUCK # 3510.     THIS SHIPMENT WAS NOT DECLARED AS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.     CLEAR OF SCENE: 1000 EST.
